.TH "WHEN" "1" "2026\-04\-17" "Winix" "User Commands"
.SH NAME
when \- convert timestamps between formats, apply time arithmetic, and
calculate durations
.SH SYNOPSIS
\f[B]when\f[R] [\f[I]options\f[R]] \f[I]input\f[R]
[\f[I]+/\-offset\f[R]]
.PP
\f[B]when\f[R] [\f[I]options\f[R]] \f[B]diff\f[R] \f[I]time1\f[R]
\f[I]time2\f[R]
.SH DESCRIPTION
Converts timestamps between formats, applies time arithmetic, and
calculates durations.
Cross\-platform \(em fills the gap on Windows where no native date
conversion command exists.
.PP
Two modes of operation:
.IP \(bu 2
\f[B]Conversion mode\f[R]: parse a timestamp, optionally apply an
offset, and output the result in all formats.
.IP \(bu 2
\f[B]Diff mode\f[R]: calculate the duration between two timestamps.
.SH OPTIONS
.TP
\f[B]\(entz\f[R] \f[I]ZONE\f[R]
Display in this timezone.
Accepts both IANA timezone IDs (e.g.\ \f[B]America/New_York\f[R]) and
Windows timezone IDs (e.g.\ \f[B]Eastern Standard Time\f[R]).
.TP
\f[B]\(enutc\f[R]
Output only the UTC ISO 8601 timestamp (conversion mode).
Useful for scripting and piping.
.TP
\f[B]\(enlocal\f[R]
Output only the local ISO 8601 timestamp (conversion mode).
When combined with \f[B]\(entz\f[R], uses the specified timezone instead
of the system local timezone.
.TP
\f[B]\(eniso\f[R]
Output only the ISO 8601 duration string (diff mode).
.TP
\f[B]\(enjson\f[R]
Output results as JSON to stdout.
.TP
\f[B]\(encolor\f[R]
Force coloured output (overrides \f[B]NO_COLOR\f[R]).
.TP
\f[B]\(enno\-color\f[R]
Disable coloured output.
.TP
\f[B]\(enversion\f[R]
Show version.
.TP
\f[B]\-h\f[R], \f[B]\(enhelp\f[R]
Show help.
.TP
\f[B]\(endescribe\f[R]
Emit machine\-readable JSON metadata (flags, examples, composability).
.SH INPUT FORMATS
The following input formats are accepted:
.IP \(bu 2
Unix epoch in seconds (auto\-detected; 13\-digit numbers are treated as
milliseconds)
.IP \(bu 2
ISO 8601 date: \f[B]2024\-06\-18\f[R]
.IP \(bu 2
ISO 8601 datetime: \f[B]2024\-06\-18T16:00:00Z\f[R] (with or without
timezone offset)
.IP \(bu 2
Named month: \f[B]18 Jun 2024\f[R]
.IP \(bu 2
The keyword \f[B]now\f[R] for the current instant
.PP
Ambiguous formats (e.g.\ \f[B]06/07/2024\f[R] where month/day order is
unclear) are rejected with an error.
.SH OFFSET FORMATS
Offsets are prefixed with \f[B]+\f[R] or \f[B]\-\f[R] and support three
syntaxes:
.IP \(bu 2
Duration shorthand: \f[B]+7d\f[R], \f[B]\-2h30m\f[R], \f[B]+90s\f[R]
(units: \f[B]d\f[R] days, \f[B]h\f[R] hours, \f[B]m\f[R] minutes,
\f[B]s\f[R] seconds)
.IP \(bu 2
ISO 8601 duration: \f[B]+P1DT12H\f[R]
.IP \(bu 2
Time span: \f[B]+01:30:00\f[R] (HH:MM:SS)
